---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-morocco', text: 'Leaving Moroccan Healthcare', level: 2 },
  { id: 'european-focus', text: 'European Focus', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'popular-destinations', text: 'Popular Destinations', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Allianz Care Review', href: '/providers/allianz-care' },
  { title: 'Best Europe Insurance', href: '/best/europe-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best French Expat Insurance', href: '/best/french-expat-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best Spanish Expat Insurance', href: '/best/spanish-expat-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'frenchSupport', header: 'French Support' },
  { key: 'euNetwork', header: 'EU Network' },
  { key: 'moroccoCoverage', header: 'Morocco Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', frenchSupport: 'Yes', euNetwork: 'Strong', moroccoCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '€165/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', frenchSupport: 'Yes', euNetwork: 'Excellent', moroccoCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '€160/mo' },
  { provider: 'April International', frenchSupport: 'Full', euNetwork: 'Strong', moroccoCoverage: 'Add-on', price: '€150/mo' },
  { provider: 'AXA Global', frenchSupport: 'Yes', euNetwork: 'Strong', moroccoCoverage: 'Included', price: '€170/mo' },
  { provider: 'Saham Assurance', frenchSupport: 'Full', euNetwork: 'Limited', moroccoCoverage: 'Included', price: '€100/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Moroccan Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Moroccan expats. Find coverage for France, Spain, Belgium, and other European destinations with French language support."
  headline="Best Insurance for Moroccan Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Morocco's diaspora is concentrated in Europe, especially France, Spain, and Belgium. Here's how to stay covered with French-language support."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/moroccan-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Moroccan expats are concentrated in France, Spain, Italy, Belgium, Netherlands, and Germany. European healthcare systems vary—understanding your destination's system and supplementing appropriately is key. Here's what we recommend:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Moroccan expats. Strong EU networks, French support, comprehensive coverage.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Excellent for European destinations. Strong EU networks, competitive pricing.</li>
    <li><strong>April International:</strong> French insurer with full French support. Excellent for France-bound expats.</li>
    <li><strong>AXA Global:</strong> Good coverage with Morocco often included. Strong European presence.</li>
    <li><strong>Saham Assurance:</strong> Moroccan insurer with some international options. Full French/Arabic support.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="French Language Support"
    description="Most Moroccan expats speak French. Look for insurers with full French-language support—April International and local French insurers excel here. This matters during medical emergencies."
    buttonText="Compare French-Support Options"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-morocco">Leaving Moroccan Healthcare</h2>
  <p>
    Morocco has multiple healthcare coverage systems. Here's what happens when you leave:
  </p>

  <h3>AMO (Assurance Maladie Obligatoire)</h3>
  <p>
    Morocco's mandatory health insurance covers formal sector employees through CNSS (private sector) or CNOPS (public sector). Coverage is tied to Moroccan employment and doesn't extend internationally.
  </p>

  <h3>RAMED</h3>
  <p>
    The medical assistance regime for low-income residents only works in Morocco. There's no international coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Private Moroccan Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Private health insurance from Moroccan companies (Saham, Wafa Assurance, RMA Watanya) typically provides limited international coverage—usually emergency treatment abroad for short periods. Living overseas requires dedicated international insurance.
  </p>

  <h3>Bilateral Agreements</h3>
  <p>
    Morocco has social security agreements with some countries (France, Belgium, Netherlands, Spain). These may provide limited healthcare coordination, but comprehensive private insurance is still recommended.
  </p>

  <h2 id="european-focus">European Focus</h2>
  <p>
    Most Moroccan expats live in Europe. Understanding European healthcare is important:
  </p>

  <h3>France</h3>
  <p>
    Largest Moroccan diaspora. Legal residents can access the French healthcare system (Sécurité sociale). Many Moroccans supplement with mutuelle (complementary insurance). Private international insurance provides comprehensive coverage during transitions.
  </p>

  <h3>Spain</h3>
  <p>
    Second largest European destination. Spanish healthcare covers legal residents. Private insurance provides faster access and choice. Proximity to Morocco makes visits easy.
  </p>

  <h3>Belgium</h3>
  <p>
    Significant Moroccan community. Belgian mandatory insurance (mutualité) covers residents. Private insurance supplements public coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Italy and Netherlands</h3>
  <p>
    Growing Moroccan communities. Both have comprehensive public healthcare for legal residents. Private insurance provides additional options.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">EU Healthcare Access</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      As a non-EU citizen, your healthcare access depends on your visa and residence status. Legal residents typically access public healthcare, but private insurance ensures coverage during transitions and provides better access.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global offers comprehensive international coverage with strong EU networks. French-language support is available. Plans come in three tiers with coverage up to unlimited.
  </p>

  <p>
    Morocco coverage can be added for visits home. Direct billing at major European hospitals.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Moroccan expats who want reliable coverage across Europe with French support.
  </p>

  <h3>Allianz Care</h3>
  <p>
    Allianz Care offers excellent European coverage at competitive prices. Strong networks throughout the EU—particularly valuable for Moroccan expats in multiple European countries.
  </p>

  <p>
    French support available. Morocco coverage can be added.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Moroccan expats in EU countries who want strong European networks at good value.
  </p>

  <h3>April International</h3>
  <p>
    April International is a French insurer with full French-language support. Excellent for Moroccan expats in France. Strong EU coverage and understanding of French healthcare system.
  </p>

  <p>
    Popular among Francophone expats from North Africa.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Moroccan expats in France who want native French service.
  </p>

  <h3>AXA Global</h3>
  <p>
    AXA has presence in Morocco and Europe. Morocco coverage is often included automatically. Strong European networks with French support available.
  </p>

  <p>
    Good option for those who want seamless Morocco coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Moroccan expats who visit home frequently and want included Morocco coverage.
  </p>

  <h3>Saham Assurance</h3>
  <p>
    Saham is one of Morocco's largest insurers and offers some international products. Full French and Arabic service, familiar brand, Morocco coverage included. International networks are more limited.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Moroccan expats who prefer familiar Moroccan service and primarily need Morocco coverage.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Compare European Coverage"
    description="Focus on EU network strength and French support when comparing. Your destination's public healthcare may provide base coverage—private insurance supplements it."
    buttonText="Get Free Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="popular-destinations">Popular Destinations</h2>
  <p>
    Insurance needs vary by destination. Here's what Moroccan expats should consider:
  </p>

  <h3>France</h3>
  <p>
    Largest Moroccan community abroad, especially in Paris, Lyon, and Marseille. French healthcare is excellent for legal residents. Private insurance (mutuelle) is common to cover copays and enhance access. Many Moroccan-origin doctors practice in France.
  </p>

  <h3>Spain</h3>
  <p>
    Close proximity to Morocco. Spanish healthcare covers legal residents. Private insurance provides faster access. Madrid and Barcelona have Moroccan communities.
  </p>

  <h3>Belgium</h3>
  <p>
    Significant community, especially in Brussels. Belgian healthcare is comprehensive for residents. French-speaking regions align with Moroccan French speakers.
  </p>

  <h3>Italy</h3>
  <p>
    Growing Moroccan community. Italian healthcare covers legal residents. Private insurance supplements public access.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Does Moroccan insurance cover me in Europe?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Moroccan insurance provides very limited international coverage (emergency only, short periods). Living in Europe requires either public healthcare access or dedicated international insurance.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I access French healthcare?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Legal residents can access French Sécurité sociale. Private mutuelle insurance supplements this. International insurance covers transitions and provides additional benefits.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about bilateral agreements?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Morocco has social security agreements with several EU countries. These provide some coordination but comprehensive private insurance is still recommended.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about coverage during Morocco visits?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">AXA and Saham include Morocco automatically. Other insurers offer Morocco as a coverage region. Confirm with your provider.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is April or Cigna better for France?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">April offers native French service and French healthcare expertise. Cigna has broader global networks. For France specifically, April may have advantages.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Are there Moroccan doctors in Europe?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">Yes, many Moroccan-origin doctors practice in France, Belgium, and other European countries. Your insurer covers any qualified doctor.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Moroccan expats in Europe have good options. Public healthcare covers legal residents in most EU countries. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> provides reliable supplementary coverage with French support. <strong>Allianz Care</strong> offers excellent EU networks at good value.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>April International</strong> is ideal for France-bound expats who want native French service. <strong>AXA Global</strong> suits those who want included Morocco coverage. <strong>Saham</strong> works for those preferring familiar Moroccan service.
  </p>

  <p>
    Understand your destination's public healthcare access. Private insurance supplements this and ensures coverage during transitions and for enhanced access.
  </p>

</PageShell>
